   https://www.cirad.fr/en/news/all-news-items/press-releases/2019/innovat
   ions-sustainable-food-systems
   https://www.cirad.fr/en/news/all-news-items/press-releases/2019/innovat
   ions-sustainable-food-systems <p> Twelve food innovations in ten cities
   worldwide are are currently the object of close scrutiny via a
   participatory methodology for assessing sustainability. The aim of the
   Urbal project, coordinated by CIRAD*, is to provide project leaders,
   donors and decision-makers with a lightweight, open-source method for
   characterizing the impacts of innovations on food system
   sustainability. The results of initial tests of the method, on three
   food innovations developed in Brasilia, Rabat and Montpellier, are
   promising. They were due to serve as examples on 10 October at a <a
   href="https://www.agropolis.fr/pdf/actu/urbal-tr-oct19.pdf "
   target="_self" rel="self" rev="width:100_height:100">round table</a> on
   the last day of the <a
   href="/en/news/all-news-items/articles/2019/evenement/urban-food-policy
   -milan-pact" target="_self" rel="self"
   rev="width:100_height:100">meeting of mayors of signatory cities to the
   Milan Pact, in Montpellier</a>. </p> Wed, 09 Oct 2019 12:51:47 +0200
   https://www.cirad.fr/en/news/all-news-items/articles/2019/science/antan
   anarivo-green-city
   https://www.cirad.fr/en/news/all-news-items/articles/2019/science/antan
   anarivo-green-city <p> From the air, the Madagascan capital looks
   remarkably green, despite its three million inhabitants. This is
   because almost half its land area is given over to farming, and one in
   every five households is at least partly involved in producing food.
   This new information comes from the Légende project, coordinated by
   CIRAD, and is very precious, at a time when the future urban
   development plan for the city is under discussion. Antananarivo would
   well serve as an example at the 5th Milan Pact Summit, which began on 7
   October in Montpellier. </p> Mon, 07 Oct 2019 15:16:57 +0200
